                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>Each number above has a corresponding power of ten and this power of ten will be important as we start to work with the content in this section.</p>

        <p>This descriptive language also covers even larger numbers: trillion, quadrillion, quintillion, sextillion, septillion, and so on.  There's also corresponding language to describe very small numbers, such as thousandth, millionth, billionth, trillionth, etc. </p>
    
        <p>Through centuries of scientific progress, humanity became increasingly aware of very large numbers and very small numbers.  As one example, the star that is nearest to our sun is Proxima Centauri.  Proxima Centauri is about 4.24 light years from our sun.  (<url href="https://imagine.gsfc.nasa.gov/features/cosmic/nearest_star_info.html"/>)  That means that light from Proxima Centauri takes about 4 years and 3 months to reach the sun.  To give us some perspective, light travels from the sun to the Earth in about 8 minutes, 20 seconds.</p>
    
        <p>In more familiar units, Proxima Centauri is about 40,208,000,000,000 kilometers from our sun.  Again, many will find the descriptive language easier to digest: Proxima Centauri is about 40.2 trillion kilometers from our sun.  </p>
    
        <p>To make computations involving such number more manageable, a standardized notation called <term>scientific notation</term> was been established.  The foundation of scientific notation is the fact that multiplying or dividing by a power of 10 will move the decimal point of a number so many places to the right or left, respectively.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-mult-div-powers-ten">
            <statement>
                <p>Perform the following operations: <ol>
                    <li><p>Multiply <m>5.7</m> by <m>10</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Multiply <m>3.1</m> by <m>10{,}000</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Divide <m>6.4</m> by <m>1{,}000</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Divide <m>9.3</m> by <m>100{,}000</m>.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol>
                    <li><p><m>5.7 \times 10 = 57</m></p>
                        <p><m>10 = 10^1</m>and multiplying by <m>10^1</m> moved the decimal point one place to the right.</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>3.1 \times 10000=31{,}000</m></p>
                        <p><m>10,000 = 10^4</m> and multiplying by <m>10^4</m> moved the decimal point four places to the right.</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>3.1 \div 1000 = 0.0064</m></p>
                        <p><m>1,000 = 10^3</m> and dividing by <m>10^3</m> moved the decimal point three places to the left.</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>9.3 \div 100000 = 0.000093</m></p>
                        <p><m>100,000 = 10^5</m> and  dividing by <m>10^5</m> moved the decimal five places to the left.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Multiplying a number by <m>10^n</m> where <m>n</m> is a positive integer had the effect of moving the decimal point <m>n</m> places to the right, while dividing by <m>10^n</m> where <m>n</m> is a positive integer had the effect of moving the decimal point <m>n</m> places to the left.</p>

        <p>Every number can be written as a product of a number between 1 and 10 and a power of 10. For example, <m>650 = 6.5 \times 100</m>.  Since <m>100 = 10^2</m>, we can also write <m>650 = 6.5 \cdot 10^{2}</m>.  The power of 10 being used is called the number's <term>order of magnitude</term>. 650 has order of magnitude 2 and 650 written in scientific notation is <m>6.5 \times 10^{2}</m>.</p>

        <definition xml:id="definition-scientific-notation">
            <statement>
                <p>A positive number is in <term>scientific notation</term> when it has the form <m>a \times 10^n</m> where <m>1 \le a \lt 10 </m> and <m>n</m> is an integer. <m>n</m> is called the number's <term>order of magnitude</term>. </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
    
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Scientific Notation for Large Numbers</title>
        
        <p>To write a numbers larger than <m>10</m> in scientific notation, we write a decimal point after the first non-zero digit of the number and then count the number of places between where the decimal point originally was and where it now is.  That number of place values is the order of magnitude of the number and becomes the exponent placed on the <m>10</m>.  Numbers larger than or equal to 10 will always have a positive exponent on ten and therefore a positive order of magnitude. </p>

        <p>If we stop and this about this for a moment, we're taking a large number and reducing it to a number between one and ten.  To have this number keep the same value, we need to multipy by a positive power of 10.  </p>
    
        <p> For example, we can write Proxima Centauri's distance to the sun (about 40,208,000,000,000 km) in scientific notation by first placing the decimal point after the <m>4</m> to obtain <m>4.0208</m> and then multiplying this by <m>10^{13}</m>, the magnitude of the original number.  Proxima Centauri's distance to our sun is about <m>4.0208 \times 10^{13}</m> km.</p>

        <p>Writing out in standard notation, 4 being followed by 13 other digits quickly communicates the size of the number.  Scientific notation communicates the size of a number and the order of magnitude just as quickly, but with no need to write long strings of zeros or to try to decipher the language of quintillions, sextillions, etc.  </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
            <p>To get a sense of how scientific notation works, let's consider familiar lengths of time converted to seconds.</p>
            
