        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Write each of the following in scientific notation:<ol>
                    <li><p>the federal debt at the close of business on Sept. 30, 2016: about 19,600,000,000,000  dollars</p></li>
                    <li><p>the world's population in 2016: about 7,418,000,000 people (<url href="http://www.prb.org/pdf16/prb-wpds2016-web-2016.pdf" />)</p></li>
                    <li><p>the earth's diameter: about 12,700,000 meters</p></li>
                    <li><p>Avogadro's number: about 602,200,000,000,000,000,000,000</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol>
                    <li><p>To convert the federal debt to scientific notation, we must first move the decimal behind the first non-zero digit: 1.96.  We must also recognize that when we move the decimal point between the <m>1</m> and <m>9</m>, we moved the decimal 13 places: <me>
                    1\overbrace{9{,}600{,}000{,}000{,}000}^{13\text{ places}} = 1.96\times 10^{13}
                    </me> Since we moved the decimal point 13 places, the federal debt can be written as <m>1.96\times 10^{13}</m> dollars at the close of business on Sept. 30, 2016.</p></li>
                    
                    <li><p>To convert the world's population into scientific notaiton, we start by placing the decimal behind the leading <m>7</m>: <m>7. 418</m>.  In doing this, we moved the decimal point 12 places:<me>
                   7{,}\overbrace{418 000 000}^{12 \text{places}} = 7.418 \times 10^{12}
                    </me> Having moved the decimal point 12 places, the order of magnitude of this number is 12 and the world's population in 2016 was about <m>7.418 \times 10^{12}</m>  people.</p></li>

                    <li><p>We'll place the decimal in <m>12,700,000</m> between the <m>1</m> and <m>2</m> and our scientific notation will begin with <m>1.27</m>.  Now taking into account the original number was greater than 10 and the fact that we moved the decimal point <m>7</m> places, the diameter of the earth is about <m>1.27\times 10^{7}</m> meters.</p></li>

                    <li><p>Anyone who's had a chemistry class is probably familar with Avogadro's number.  To convert this into scientific notation, we place the decimal point behind the 6 and count that we've moved the decimal point <m>23</m> places, giving us <m>6.022\times 10^{23}</m> for Avogadro's number written in scientific notation.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

