    <subsection>
        <title>Scientific Notation for Small Numbers</title>

        <p>Scientific notation can also be extremely useful when working with numbers smaller than <m>1</m> as well.  To work with scientific notation and numbers smaller than <m>1</m>, consider our earlier example, Example <xref ref="example-mult-div-powers-ten" />.  These results of the last two parts were decimals small than 1.  </p>

        <p>When we convert a decimal smaller than 1 into scientific notation, we need to divide by a power of 10 instead of multiplying.</p>

        <p>For example, <m>0.05 = 5 \div 100</m> or <m>5 \div 10^2</m>.  The second representation, <m>5 \div 10^2</m>, is very close to scientific notation, except for the fact that we're dividing by <m>10^2</m>.  We need to have a way to rewrite <q><m>\div 10^2</m></q> as multiplication. If we think back to our work with negative exponents, we'll find our answer.  </p>

        <p>We can take our number, <m>5 \div 10^2</m> and think of it as a fraction <m>\dfrac{5}{10^2}</m>.  Using negative exponents, we can rewrite this as <m>5\times10^{-2}</m> and we now have 0.05 written in scientific notation: <m>0.05 = 5\times10^{-2}</m></p>
    
        <example>
            <p>In quantum mechanics, there is an important value called the Planck Constant. Its units, joule-seconds, are units of physical action, that's energy multiplied by time. (<url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planck_constant" />) </p>
            <p>Written as a decimal, the value of the Planck constant (rounded to 4 significant digits) is <m>0.0000000000000000000000000000000006626</m> joule-seconds.</p>
            
            <p>It's a bit dizzying to look at that decimal and even to count out how many <m>0</m>s are in it.  Some folks use spaces every three digits after a decimal to help us to count the zeros. If we do this, then we'd have <m>0.000~000~000~000~000~000~000~000~000~000~000~662~6</m> joule-seconds. With the spaces included,  we can count the zeros more easily. Still, it's challenging to both put this number into words or use it in a calculation.  </p>

            <p>Scientific notation, however, quickly communicates both the value and the order of magnitude of the Planck constant.  In scientific notation, the Planck constant is <m>6.626 \times 10^{-34}</m> joule-seconds.  In this form, it will be much easier to use <m>6.626 \times 10^{-34}</m> in a calculation.</p>
        </example>
        
        <p>The fact that we now have negative powers of ten should stand out as being different from what occurred with the large numbers.  If we try to use powers of ten to get from 6.626 to the Planck Constant, we clearly cannot multiply by positive powers of ten.  This would only give us a number larger than 6.626 and clearly the Plank Constant is very, very small.  A negative power of ten means that we're really dividing by that power of ten.</p>

        <p>To write a small number in scientific notation, we start as we did before and place the decimal point behind the first non-zero digit.  We then count the number of decimal places between where the decimal had originally been and where it now is.  This becomes the number's order of magnitude and the power of ten.  The key difference is that these powers are negative numbers.</p>

        <example>
           <statement>
                <p>Write each of the following in scientific notation:<ol>
                    <li><p>the weight of a single grain of long grain rice: about 0.029 grams <!-- (<url href="http://www.bluebulbprojects.com/measureofthings/results.php?comp=weight&unit=gms&amt=3.0E-7&sort=pr&p=1"/>) --></p></li> 
                    <li><p>the weight of a poppy seed: about 0.0000003 kilograms <!-- (<url href="http://www.bluebulbprojects.com/measureofthings/results.php?comp=weight&unit=kgms&amt=3.0E-7&sort=pr&p=1"/>) --></p> </li> 
                    <li><p>the gate pitch of a microprocessor: 0.000000014 meters (14 nm) (<url href="http://www.prb.org/pdf16/prb-wpds2016-web-2016.pdf"/>)</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol>
                    <li><p>To convert the weight of a single grain of long grain rice to scientific notation, we must first move the decimal behind the first non-zero digit to obtain 2.9.  We must also recognize that when we move the decimal point between the <m>2</m> and <m>9</m>, we moved the decimal 2 places. Since 0.029 is smaller than one, <m>0.029 = 2.9 \times 10^{-2}</m>.</p></li>
                    
                    <li><p>To convert the weight of a poppy seed into scientific notation, we start by placing the decimal behind the <m>3</m>.  In doing this, we moved the decimal point 7 places:<me>
                   0.\overbrace{0000003}^{7 \text{ places}} = 3 \times 10^{-7}
                    </me> Having moved the decimal point 7 places, the order of magnitude of this number is -7 and the weight of a poppy seed is about <m>3 \times 10^{-7}</m> grams.</p></li>

                    <li><p> To convert 0.000000014 meters into scientific notation, we'll move the decimal point behind the <m>1</m> and count the number of places that the decimal point moved: <me>
                        0.\overbrace{00000001}^{8 \text{ places}}4 = 1.4 \times 10^{-8}
                    </me> The gate pitch of a microprocessor is <m>1.4 \times 10^{-8}</m> meters.</p></li>

                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

