        <p>Often times when we are multiply or dividing numbers in scientific notation, the resulting value will not be in scientific notation.  Suppose we were multiplying <m>\left( 9.3\times 10^{17} \right)\left( 8.2 \times 10^{-6} \right)</m> and need to state our answer using scientific notation.  We'd start as we've previously done:<md>
            <mrow> \left( 9.3\times 10^{17} \right)\left( 8.2 \times 10^{-6} \right) \amp=
                    \left( 9.3\times 8.2 \right)\times \left( 10^{17} \times 10^{-6} \right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= 76.26 \times 10^{11} </mrow>
        </md> While this is correct, the answer is not written using scientific notation. One ways to covert this answer into scientific notation if to turn just the coefficient into scientific notation and momentarily ignore the power of ten: <md>
            <mrow> \phantom{\left( 9.3\times 10^{17} \right)\left( 8.2 \times 10^{-6} \right)} \amp=
                         \highlight{76.26} \times 10^{11} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= \highlight{7.626 \times 10^1} \times 10^11 </mrow>
        </md> Now that the coefficient fits into the proper format, we can combine the powers of ten and have our answer written using scientific notation. <md>
            <mrow> \phantom{\left( 9.3\times 10^{17} \right)\left( 8.2 \times 10^{-6} \right)} \amp=
                        7.626 \times \highlight{10^1 \times 10^{11}} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= 7.626 \times 10^{{11}} </mrow>
        </md>

        </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
            <p>Multiply or divide as indicated.  Write your answer using scientific notation. <ol>
                <li><m>\left( 8.6 \times 10^{21} \right)\left( 3.2 \times 10^{-7} \right)</m></li>
                <li><m>\dfrac{  8.6 \times 10^{21} }{ 3.2 \times 10^{-7} }</m></li>
                <li><m>\left( 1.6 \times 10^{-6} \right)\left( 8 \times 10^{-19} \right)</m></li>
                <li><m>\dfrac{ 1.6 \times 10^{-6}  }{ 8 \times 10^{-19} }</m></li>
            </ol></p></statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Again, we'll separate out the work for the coefficients from the work for the powers of ten.  If the resulting coefficient is not between one and 10, we'll need to adjust that coefficient to put it into scientific notaiton.<ol>
                <li><p><md>
                    <mrow> \left( 8.6 \times 10^{21} \right)\left( 3.2 \times 10^{-7} \right) \amp= 
                                \left( 8.6 \times 3.2 \right)\times\left( 10^{21} \times 10^{-7} \right)     </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp= \highlight{27.52} \times 10^{14} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp= \highlight{2.752\times 10^1} \times 10^{14} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp=  2.752 \times 10^{15} </mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                <li><p>We need to remember to apply the <xref ref="exponent-rules-product" autoname="title" />  for exponents to the powers of ten.<md>
                    <mrow>  \dfrac{  8.6 \times 10^{21} }{ 3.2 \times 10^{-7} }  \amp= 
                                    \dfrac{  8.6 }{ 3.2  }   \times \dfrac{  10^{21} }{  10^{-7} }    </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp= 2.6875 \times 10^{28} </mrow>
                    </md>We need to apply the <xref ref="exponent-rules-quotient" autoname="title" />  for exponents to the powers of ten and to remember that <m>21-(-7) = 21+7</m>. </p></li>
                <li><p><md>
                    <mrow>  \left( 1.6 \times 10^{-6} \right)\left( 8 \times 10^{-19} \right)  \amp= 
                                 \left( 1.6 \times 8 \right)\times \left( 10^{-6} \times 10^{-19} \right) </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp= \highlight{12.8} \times 10^{-25} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp= \highlight{1.28\times 10^1} \times 10^{-25} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp=  1.28 \times 10^{-24} </mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                <li><p><md>
                    <mrow> \dfrac{ 1.6 \times 10^{-6}  }{ 8 \times 10^{-19} }  \amp= 
                               \dfrac{ 1.6  }{ 8 }\times\dfrac{ 10^{-6}  }{ 10^{-19} }      </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp= \highlight{0.2} \times 10^{13} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp= \highlight{2\times 10^{-1}} \times 10^{13} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp=  2 \times 10^{12} </mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <exercise>
            <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/NumberBasics/ScientificNotation80.pg" seed="3002"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/NumberBasics/ScientificNotation100.pg" seed="1000"/>
        </exercise>

        <p>There are times where we will have to raise numbers written in scientific notation to a power.  For example, suppose we have to find the area of a square whose radius is <m>3\times 10^7</m> feet.  To perform this calculation, we first remember the formula for the area of a square, <m>A=s^2</m> and then substitute  <m>3\times 10^7</m> for <m>s</m>: <m>A = \left( 3\times 10^7 \right)^2</m>.  To perform this calculation, we'll need to remember to use the <xref ref="exponent-rules-product-to-a-power" autoname="title" /> and the <xref ref="exponent-rules-power-to-a-power" autoname="title" /> exponent rules: <md>
            <mrow> A \amp=  \left( 3\times 10^7 \right)^2</mrow>
            <mrow>  \amp= \left( 3\right)^2 \times \left(10^7 \right)^2</mrow>
            <mrow>  \amp=  9 \times 10^{14} </mrow>
        </md></p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p> Perform the indicated operation.  Write your answer using scientific notation. <ol>
                    <li><p><m> \left( 4.3 \times 10^{-6} \right)^3 </m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\left( 1.6 \times 10^{-7} \right)^{-2}</m></p></li>
                </ol> </p>
            </statement> 
            <solution>
                <p> We'll start each example by applying the outer exponent to each factor in the product.  Depending on the resulting coefficient, we might need to convert the coefficient back into scientific notation.<ol>
                    <li><p><md>
                        <mrow>\left( 4.3 \times 10^{-6} \right)^3 \amp= \left( 4.3 \right)^3 \times \left(10^{-6} \right)^3</mrow>
                        <mrow>  \amp= \highlight{79.507} \times 10^{-18}  </mrow>
                        <mrow>  \amp= \highlight{7.9507\times 10^1} \times 10^{-18}  </mrow>
                        <mrow>  \amp= 7.9507\times 10^{-17}  </mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p><md>
                        <mrow>\left( 1.6 \times 10^{-7} \right)^{-2} \amp= \left( 1.6 \right)^{-2} \times \left( 10^{-7} \right)^{-2} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp= \highlight{0.390625} \times 10 ^{14} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp= \highlight{3.90625 \times 10^{-1}} \times 10 ^{14} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp= 3.90625 \times 10 ^{13} </mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                </ol> </p>
            </solution>
        </example>


